# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: j1939
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A **controller area network** (**CAN**) is a vehicle bus standard designed to enable efficient communication primarily between electronic control units (ECUs).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Originally developed to reduce the complexity and cost of electrical wiring in automobiles through multiplexing, the CAN bus protocol has since been adopted in various other contexts, such as 3D printing.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This broadcast-based, message-oriented protocol ensures data integrity and prioritization through a process called arbitration, allowing the highest priority device to continue transmitting if multiple devices attempt to send data simultaneously, while others back off.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Its reliability is enhanced by differential signaling, which mitigates electrical noise.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If one side of the differential signal is lost, the system can switch to one wire communication.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This is to ensure data communication for critical systems.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Common versions of the CAN protocol include CAN 2.0, CAN FD, and CAN XL which vary in their data rate capabilities and maximum data payload sizes.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Development of the CAN bus started in 1983 at Robert Bosch GmbH.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The protocol was officially released in 1986 at the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) conference in Detroit, Michigan.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The first CAN controller chips were introduced by Intel in 1987, and shortly thereafter by Philips.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Released in 1991, the Mercedes-Benz W140 was the first production vehicle to feature a CAN-based multiplex wiring system.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Bosch published several versions of the CAN specification.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The latest is CAN 2.0, published in 1991.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Part A is for the standard format with an 11-bit identifier, and part B is for the extended format with a 29-bit identifier.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A CAN device that uses 11-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0A, and a CAN device that uses 29-bit identifiers is commonly called CAN 2.0B.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] These standards are freely available from Bosch along with other specifications and white papers.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In 1993, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) released CAN standard ISO 11898, which was later restructured into two parts: ISO 11898-1 which covers the data link layer, and ISO 11898-2 which covers the CAN physical layer for high-speed CAN.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-3 was released later and covers the CAN physical layer for low-speed, fault-tolerant CAN.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The physical layer standards ISO 11898-2 and ISO 11898-3 are not part of the Bosch CAN 2.0 specification.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In 2012, Bosch released CAN FD 1.0, or CAN with Flexible Data-Rate.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This specification uses a different frame format that allows a different data length as well as optionally switching to a faster bit rate after the arbitration is decided.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN FD is compatible with existing CAN 2.0 networks so new CAN FD devices can coexist on the same network with existing CAN devices, using the same CAN 2.0 communication parameters.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] As of 2018, Bosch was active in extending CAN standards.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The CAN bus is one of five protocols used in the on-board diagnostics (OBD)-II vehicle diagnostics standard.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The OBD-II standard has been mandatory for all cars and light trucks sold in the United States since model year 1996.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The EOBD standard has been mandatory for all petrol vehicles sold in the European Union since 2001 and all diesel vehicles since 2004.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The modern automobile may have as many as 70 electronic control units (ECUs) for various subsystems.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Usually the biggest processor is the engine control unit.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Others are used for autonomous driving, advanced driver assistance system (ADAS), transmission, airbags, antilock braking/ABS, cruise control, electric power steering, audio systems, power windows, doors, mirror adjustment, battery and recharging systems for hybrid/electric cars, etc.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Some of these form independent subsystems, but communication among others is essential.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A subsystem may need to control actuators or receive feedback from sensors.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard was devised to fill this need.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In recent years, the LIN bus (Local Interconnect Network) standard has been introduced to complement CAN for non-critical subsystems such as air-conditioning and infotainment, where data transmission speed and reliability are less critical.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN bus is often used to connect 3D printer mainboards to expansion boards due to its high electrical noise tolerance, especially from ground noise generated by stepper motors, commonly used in 3D printers and other CNC applications.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The CAN FD variant is used by many, such as the Duet3D controller family, as it has higher bandwidth needed to support the high command rates of 3D printing.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Due to its legacy, CAN 2.0 is the most widely used protocol with a maximum payload size of eight bytes and a typical baud rate of 500 kbit/s.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Classical CAN, which includes CAN 2.0A (Standard CAN) and CAN 2.0B (Extended CAN), primarily differs in identifier field lengths: CAN 2.0A uses an 11-bit identifier, while CAN 2.0B employs a 29-bit identifier.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The longer identifier in CAN 2.0B allows for a greater number of unique message identifiers, which is beneficial in complex systems with many nodes and data types.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] However, this increase in unique message identifiers also increases frame length, which in turn reduces the maximum data rate.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Additionally, the extended identifier provides finer control over message prioritization due to more available identifier values.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This, however, may introduce compatibility issues; CAN 2.0A devices can generally communicate with CAN 2.0B devices, but not vice versa, due to potential errors in handling longer identifiers.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 1 Mbit/s and is the basis for higher-layer protocols.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In contrast, low-speed CAN 2.0 supports bit rates from 40 kbit/s to 125 kbit/s and offers fault tolerance by allowing communication to continue despite a fault in one of the two wires, with each node maintaining its own termination.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN FD (Flexible Data-Rate), standardized as ISO 11898-1, was developed by Bosch and released in 2012 to meet the need for increased data transfer in modern high-performance vehicles.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN FD also introduces a flexible data field size, increasing the maximum size from 8 bytes to 64 bytes.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This flexibility allows for more efficient data transmission by reducing the number of frames needed for large data transfers, which is beneficial for applications like high-resolution sensor data or software updates.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN FD maintains backward compatibility with CAN 2.0 devices by using the same frame format as CAN 2.0B, with the addition of a new control field to indicate whether the frame is a CAN FD frame or a standard CAN 2.0 frame.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This allows CAN FD devices to coexist with CAN 2.0 devices on the same bus, while higher data rates and larger data payloads are available only when communicating with other CAN FD devices.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN XL, specified by CiA 610-1 and standardized as part of ISO11898-1, supports up to 2,048-byte payloads and data rates up to 20 Mbit/s.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] It bridges the gap between CAN FD and Ethernet (100BASE-T1) while maintaining CAN's collision-resolution benefits.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN XL controllers can also handle Classical CAN and CAN FD communication, ensuring compatibility in mixed networks.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Its large data fields allow for higher layer protocols like IP (Internet Protocol) and the tunneling of Ethernet frames.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Most of the CAN standard applies to the transfer layer.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer receives messages from the physical layer and transmits those messages to the object layer.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The transfer layer is responsible for bit timing and synchronization, message framing, arbitration, acknowledgment, error detection and signaling, and fault confinement.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN bus (ISO 11898-1:2003) originally specified the link layer protocol with only abstract requirements for the physical layer, e.g., asserting the use of a medium with multiple-access at the bit level through the use of dominant and recessive states.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The electrical aspects of the physical layer (voltage, current, number of conductors) were specified in ISO 11898-2:2003, which is now widely accepted.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] However, the mechanical aspects of the physical layer (connector type and number, colors, labels, pin-outs) have yet to be formally specified.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] As a result, an automotive ECU will typically have a particular—often custom—connector with various sorts of cables, of which two are the CAN bus lines.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This *de facto* mechanical standard for CAN could be implemented with the node having both male and female 9-pin D-sub connectors electrically wired to each other in parallel within the node.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Bus power is fed to a node's male connector and the bus draws power from the node's female connector.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This follows the electrical engineering convention that power sources are terminated at female connectors.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Adoption of this standard avoids the need to fabricate custom splitters to connect two sets of bus wires to a single D connector at each node.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Such nonstandard (custom) wire harnesses (splitters) that join conductors outside the node reduce bus reliability, eliminate cable interchangeability, reduce compatibility of wiring harnesses, and increase cost.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The absence of a complete physical layer specification (mechanical in addition to electrical) freed the CAN bus specification from the constraints and complexity of physical implementation.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] However, it left CAN bus implementations open to interoperability issues due to mechanical incompatibility.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In order to improve interoperability, many vehicle makers have generated specifications describing a set of allowed CAN transceivers in combination with requirements on the parasitic capacitance on the line.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The allowed parasitic capacitance includes both capacitors as well as ESD protection (ESD against ISO 7637-3).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In addition to parasitic capacitance, 12V and 24V systems do not have the same requirements in terms of line maximum voltage.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Indeed, during jump start events light vehicle lines can go up to 24V while truck systems can go as high as 36V.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] New solutions are emerging, allowing the same component to be used for CAN as well as CAN FD (see ).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Noise immunity on ISO 11898-2:2003 is achieved by maintaining the differential impedance of the bus at a low level with low-value resistors (120 ohms) at each end of the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] However, when dormant, a low-impedance bus such as CAN draws more current (and power) than other voltage-based signaling buses.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] On CAN bus systems, balanced line operation, where current in one signal line is exactly balanced by current in the opposite direction in the other signal provides an independent, stable 0 V reference for the receivers.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Best practice determines that CAN bus balanced pair signals be carried in twisted pair wires in a shielded cable to minimize RF emission and reduce interference susceptibility in the already noisy RF environment of an automobile.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 provides some immunity to common mode voltage between transmitter and receiver by having a 0 V rail running along the bus to maintain a high degree of voltage association between the nodes.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Also, in the de facto mechanical configuration mentioned above, a supply rail is included to distribute power to each of the transceiver nodes.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The design provides a common supply for all the transceivers.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The actual voltage to be applied by the bus and which nodes apply to it are application-specific and not formally specified.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Common practice node design provides each node with transceivers that are optically isolated from their node host and derive a 5 V linearly regulated supply voltage for the transceivers from the universal supply rail provided by the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This usually allows operating margin on the supply rail sufficient to allow interoperability across many node types.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Typical values of supply voltage on such networks are 7 to 30 V.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] However, the lack of a formal standard means that system designers are responsible for supply rail compatibility.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] ISO 11898-2 describes the electrical implementation formed from a multi-dropped single-ended balanced line configuration with resistor termination at each end of the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In this configuration a dominant state is asserted by one or more transmitters switching the CAN− to supply 0 V and (simultaneously) switching CAN+ to the +5 V bus voltage thereby forming a current path through the resistors that terminate the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] As such the terminating resistors form an essential component of the signaling system, and are included, not just to limit wave reflection at high frequency.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] During a recessive state, the signal lines and resistor(s) remain in a high-impedance state with respect to both rails.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Voltages on both CAN+ and CAN− tend (weakly) towards a voltage midway between the rails.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A recessive state is present on the bus only when none of the transmitters on the bus is asserting a dominant state.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] During a dominant state, the signal lines and resistor(s) move to a low-impedance state with respect to the rails so that current flows through the resistor.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN+ voltage tends to +5 V and CAN− tends to 0 V.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Irrespective of signal state the signal lines are always in a low-impedance state with respect to one another by virtue of the terminating resistors at the end of the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This signaling strategy differs significantly from other balanced line transmission technologies such as RS-422/3, RS-485, etc. which employ differential line drivers/ receivers and use a signaling system based on the differential mode voltage of the balanced line crossing a notional 0 V.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on such systems normally relies on the media supporting three states (active high, active low and inactive tri-state) and is dealt with in the time domain.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Multiple access on CAN bus is achieved by the electrical logic of the system supporting just two states that are conceptually analogous to a ‘wired AND’ network.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN is a multi-master serial bus standard for connecting electronic control units (ECUs) also known as nodes (automotive electronics is a major application domain).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Two or more nodes are required on the CAN bus to communicate.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A node may interface to devices from simple digital logic e.g.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] PLD, via FPGA up to an embedded computer running extensive software.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Such a computer may also be a gateway allowing a general-purpose computer (like a laptop) to communicate over a USB or Ethernet port to the devices on a CAN bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] All nodes are connected to each other through a physically conventional *two-wire bus*.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The wires are a twisted pair with a 120 Ω (nominal) characteristic impedance.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This bus uses differential wired-AND signals.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Two signals, CAN high (CANH) and CAN low (CANL) are either driven to a "dominant" state with CANH > CANL, or not driven and pulled by passive resistors to a "recessive" state with CANH ≤ CANL.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A 0 data bit encodes a dominant state, while a 1 data bit encodes a recessive state, supporting a wired-AND convention, which gives nodes with lower ID numbers priority on the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] (Receivers consider any differential voltage of less than 0.5 V to be recessive.) The dominant differential voltage is a nominal 2 V.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The dominant common mode voltage (CANH+CANL)/2 must be within 1.5 to 3.5 V of common, while the recessive common mode voltage must be within ±12 of common.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Low-speed fault-tolerant CAN signaling operates similarly to high-speed CAN, but with larger voltage swings.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The dominant state is transmitted by driving CANH towards the device power supply voltage (5 V or 3.3 V), and CANL towards 0 V when transmitting a dominant (0), while the termination resistors pull the bus to a recessive state with CANH at 0 V and CANL at 5 V.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This allows a simpler receiver that just considers the sign of CANH−CANL.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Both wires must be able to handle −27 to +40 V without damage.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] With both high-speed and low-speed CAN, the speed of the transition is faster when a recessive-to-dominant transition occurs since the CAN wires are being actively driven.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The speed of the dominant-to-recessive transition depends primarily on the length of the CAN network and the capacitance of the wire used.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN is usually used in automotive and industrial applications where the bus runs from one end of the environment to the other.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Fault-tolerant CAN is often used where groups of nodes need to be connected together.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The specifications require the bus be kept within a minimum and maximum common mode bus voltage but do not define how to keep the bus within this range.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The termination resistors are needed to suppress reflections as well as return the bus to its recessive or idle state.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] High-speed CAN uses a 120 Ω resistor at each end of a linear bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Low-speed CAN uses resistors at each node.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Other types of terminations may be used such as the Terminating Bias Circuit defined in ISO11783.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A terminating bias circuit provides power and ground in addition to the CAN signaling on a four-wire cable.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This provides automatic electrical bias and termination at each end of each bus segment.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] An ISO11783 network is designed for hot plug-in and removal of bus segments and ECUs.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Each node is able to send and receive messages, but not simultaneously.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A message or Frame consists primarily of the ID (identifier), which represents the priority of the message, and up to eight data bytes.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A CRC, acknowledge slot [ACK] and other overhead are also part of the message.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD extends the length of the data section to up to 64 bytes per frame.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The message is transmitted serially onto the bus using a non-return-to-zero (NRZ) format and may be received by all nodes.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The devices that are connected by a CAN network are typically sensors, actuators, and other control devices.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] These devices are connected to the bus through a host processor, a CAN controller, and a CAN transceiver.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN data transmission uses a lossless bitwise arbitration method of contention resolution.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This arbitration method requires all nodes on the CAN network to be synchronized to sample every bit on the CAN network at the same time.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Unfortunately the term synchronous is imprecise since the data is transmitted in an asynchronous format, namely without a clock signal.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The CAN specifications use the terms *dominant* bits and *recessive* bits, where dominant is a logical 0 (actively driven to a voltage by the transmitter) and recessive is a logical 1 (passively returned to a voltage by a resistor).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The idle state is represented by the recessive level (Logical 1).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If one node transmits a dominant bit and another node transmits a recessive bit then there is a collision and the dominant bit wins.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This means there is no delay to the higher-priority message, and the node transmitting the lower-priority message automatically attempts to re-transmit six-bit clocks after the end of the dominant message.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This makes CAN very suitable as a real-time prioritized communications system.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The exact voltages for a logical 0 or 1 depend on the physical layer used, but the basic principle of CAN requires that each node listen to the data on the CAN network including the transmitting node(s) itself (themselves).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If a logical 1 is transmitted by all transmitting nodes at the same time, then a logical 1 is seen by all of the nodes, including both the transmitting node(s) and receiving node(s).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is transmitted by all transmitting node(s) at the same time, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If a logical 0 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, and a logical 1 is being transmitted by one or more nodes, then a logical 0 is seen by all nodes including the node(s) transmitting the logical 1.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] When a node transmits a logical 1 but sees a logical 0, it realizes that there is a contention and it quits transmitting.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] By using this process, any node that transmits a logical 1, when another node transmits a logical 0, loses the arbitration and drops out.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A node that loses arbitration re-queues its message for later transmission and the CAN frame bit-stream continues without error until only one node is left transmitting.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This means that the node that transmits the first 1 loses arbitration.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Since the 11 bit (or 29bit for CAN 2.0B) identifier is transmitted by all nodes at the start of the CAN frame, the node with the lowest identifier transmits more zeros at the start of the frame, and that is the node that wins the arbitration or has the highest priority.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] For example, consider an 11-bit ID CAN network, with two nodes with IDs of 15 (binary representation, 00000001111) and 16 (binary representation, 00000010000).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If these two nodes transmit at the same time, each will first transmit the start bit then transmit the first six zeros of their ID with no arbitration decision being made.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] When ID bit 4 is transmitted, the node with the ID of 16 transmits a 1 (recessive) for its ID, and the node with the ID of 15 transmits a 0 (dominant) for its ID.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] When this happens, the node with the ID of 16 knows it transmitted a 1, but sees a 0 and realizes that there is a collision and it lost arbitration.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Node 16 stops transmitting which allows the node with ID of 15 to continue its transmission without any loss of data.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The node with the lowest ID will always win the arbitration and therefore has the highest priority.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Bit rates up to 1 Mbit/s are possible at network lengths below 40 m.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Decreasing the bit rate allows longer network distances (e.g.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The improved CAN FD standard allows increasing the bit rate after arbitration and can increase the speed of the data section by a factor of up to ten or more of the arbitration bit rate.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] All nodes on the CAN network must operate at the same nominal bit rate, but noise, phase shifts, oscillator tolerance and oscillator drift mean that the actual bit rate might not be the nominal bit rate.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Since a separate clock signal is not used, a means of synchronizing the nodes is necessary.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is important during arbitration since the nodes in arbitration must be able to see both their transmitted data and the other nodes' transmitted data at the same time.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Synchronization is also important to ensure that variations in oscillator timing between nodes do not cause errors.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Synchronization starts with a hard synchronization on the first recessive to dominant transition after a period of bus idle (the start bit).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Resynchronization occurs on every recessive to dominant transition during the frame.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The CAN controller expects the transition to occur at a multiple of the nominal bit time.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If the transition does not occur at the exact time the controller expects it, the controller adjusts the nominal bit time accordingly.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The adjustment is accomplished by dividing each bit into a number of time slices called quanta, and assigning some number of quanta to each of the four segments within the bit: synchronization, propagation, phase segment 1 and phase segment 2.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The number of quanta the bit is divided into can vary by controller, and the number of quanta assigned to each segment can be varied depending on bit rate and network conditions.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A transition that occurs before or after it is expected causes the controller to calculate the time difference and lengthen phase segment 1 or shorten phase segment 2 by this time.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This effectively adjusts the timing of the receiver to the transmitter to synchronize them.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This resynchronization process is done continuously at every recessive to dominant transition to ensure the transmitter and receiver stay in sync.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Continuously resynchronizing reduces errors induced by noise, and allows a receiving node that was synchronized to a node that lost arbitration to resynchronize to the node which won arbitration.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Message IDs must be unique on a single CAN bus, otherwise two nodes would continue transmission beyond the end of the arbitration field (ID) causing an error.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In the early 1990s, the choice of IDs for messages was done simply on the basis of identifying the type of data and the sending node; however, as the ID is also used as the message priority, this led to poor real-time performance.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In those scenarios, a low CAN bus use of around 30% was commonly required to ensure that all messages would meet their deadlines.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] However, if IDs are instead determined based on the deadline of the message, the lower the numerical ID and hence the higher the message priority, then bus use of 70 to 80% can typically be achieved before any message deadlines are missed.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Data frames and remote frames are separated from preceding frames by a bit field called interframe space.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Interframe space consists of at least three consecutive recessive (1) bits.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Following that, if a dominant bit is detected, it will be regarded as the *Start of frame* bit of the next frame.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Overload frames and error frames are not preceded by an interframe space and multiple overload frames are not separated by an interframe space.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Interframe space contains the bit fields intermission and bus idle, and suspend transmission for error passive stations, which have been transmitter of the previous message.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A CAN network can be configured to work with two different message (or *frame*) formats: the standard or base frame format (described in CAN 2.0 A and CAN 2.0 B), and the extended frame format (described only by CAN 2.0 B).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The only difference between the two formats is that the *CAN base frame* supports a length of 11 bits for the identifier, and the *CAN extended frame* supports a length of 29 bits for the identifier, made up of the 11-bit identifier (base identifier) and an 18-bit extension (identifier extension).
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The distinction between CAN base frame format and CAN extended frame format is made by using the IDE bit, which is transmitted as dominant in case of an 11-bit frame, and transmitted as recessive in case of a 29-bit frame.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] CAN controllers that support extended frame format messages are also able to send and receive messages in CAN base frame format.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] All frames begin with a start-of-frame (SOF) bit that denotes the start of the frame transmission.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The data frame is the only frame for actual data transmission.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The CAN standard requires that the implementation must accept the base frame format and may accept the extended frame format, but must tolerate the extended frame format.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The frame format is as follows: The bit values are described for CAN-LO signal.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The two identifier fields (A & B) combine to form a 29-bit identifier.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In the event of a data frame and a remote frame with the same identifier being transmitted at the same time, the data frame wins arbitration due to the dominant RTR bit following the identifier.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The overload frame contains the two bit fields: Overload Flag and Overload Delimiter.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Detection of a dominant bit during intermission.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The start of an overload frame due to case 1 is only allowed to be started at the first bit time of an expected intermission, whereas overload frames due to case 2 start one bit after detecting the dominant bit.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Overload Flag consists of six dominant bits.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The overall form corresponds to that of the active error flag.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The overload flag's form destroys the fixed form of the intermission field.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] As a consequence, all other stations also detect an overload condition and on their part start transmission of an overload flag.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Overload Delimiter consists of eight recessive bits.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The overload delimiter is of the same form as the error delimiter.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The acknowledge slot is used to acknowledge the receipt of a valid CAN frame.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Each node that receives the frame, without finding an error, transmits a dominant level in the ACK slot and thus overrides the recessive level of the transmitter.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] If a transmitter detects a recessive level in the ACK slot, it knows that no receiver found a valid frame.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] A receiving node may transmit a recessive to indicate that it did not receive a valid frame, but another node that did receive a valid frame may override this with a dominant.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The transmitting node cannot know that the message has been received by all of the nodes on the CAN network.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Often, the mode of operation of the device is to re-transmit unacknowledged frames over and over.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This may lead to eventually entering the *error passive* state.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] To ensure enough transitions to maintain synchronization, a bit of opposite polarity is inserted after five consecutive bits of the same polarity.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This practice is called bit stuffing, and is necessary due to the non-return-to-zero (NRZ) coding used with CAN.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The stuffed data frames are destuffed by the receiver.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] All fields in the frame are stuffed with the exception of the CRC delimiter, ACK field and end of frame which are a fixed size and are not stuffed.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] In the fields where bit stuffing is used, six consecutive bits of the same polarity (111111 or 000000) are considered an error.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] An active error flag can be transmitted by a node when an error has been detected.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The active error flag consists of six consecutive dominant bits and violates the rule of bit stuffing.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Bit stuffing means that data frames may be larger than one would expect by simply enumerating the bits shown in the tables above.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] The stuffing bit itself may be the first of the five consecutive identical bits, so in the worst case there is one stuffing bit per four original bits.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] where n is the number of data bytes, a maximum of 8.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] Since $8n+44$ is the size of the frame before stuffing, in the worst case one bit will be added every four original bits after the first one (hence the −1 at the numerator) and, because of the layout of the bits of the header, only 34 out of 44 of them can be subject to bit stuffing.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] An undesirable side effect of the bit stuffing scheme is that a small number of bit errors in a received message may corrupt the destuffing process, causing a larger number of errors to propagate through the destuffed message.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This reduces the level of protection that would otherwise be offered by the CRC against the original errors.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p01] This deficiency of the protocol has been addressed in CAN FD frames by the use of a combination of fixed stuff bits and a counter that records the number of stuff bits inserted.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] As the CAN standard does not include common communication features, such as flow control, device addressing, and transportation of data blocks larger than one message, and above all, application data, many implementations of higher layer protocols were created.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Several are standardized for a business area, although all can be extended by each manufacturer.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] For passenger cars, each manufacturer has its own standard.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] CAN in Automation (CiA) is the international users' and manufacturers' organization that develops and supports CAN-based higher-layer protocols and their international standardization.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] The CANopen Special Interest Group (SIG) "Lift Control", which was founded in 2001, develops the CANopen application profile CiA 417 for lift control systems.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] It works on extending the features, improves technical content and ensures that the current legal standards for lift control systems are met.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] The first version of CiA 417 was published (available for CiA members) in summer 2003, version 2.0 in February 2010, version 2.1.0 in July 2012, version 2.2.0 in December 2015, and version 2.3.1 in February 2020.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Jörg Hellmich (ELFIN GmbH) is the chairman of this SIG and manages a wiki of the CANopen lift community with content about CANopen lift.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] CAN DBC files are standardized ASCII files used to define messages sent over a CAN bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] They define the format and purpose of each type of message, including the message IDs, signal names, scaling, offsets, and data types, and provide an interoperable aid to developing CAN bus applications.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] CAN is a low-level protocol and does not support any security features intrinsically.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] There is also no encryption in standard CAN implementations, which leaves these networks open to man-in-the-middle frame interception.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] In most implementations, applications are expected to deploy their own security mechanisms; e.g., to authenticate incoming commands or the presence of certain devices on the network.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Failure to implement adequate security measures may result in various sorts of attacks if the opponent manages to insert messages on the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] While passwords exist for some safety-critical functions, such as modifying firmware, programming keys, or controlling antilock brake actuators, these systems are not implemented universally and have a limited number of seed/key pairs.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] When developing or troubleshooting the CAN bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyse, decode and store signals so people can view the high-speed waveforms at their leisure.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] There are also specialist tools as well as CAN bus monitors.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] A CAN bus monitor is an analysis tool, often a combination of hardware and software, used during development of hardware that uses the CAN bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Typically the CAN bus monitor will listen to the traffic on the CAN bus in order to display it in a user interface.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Often the CAN bus monitor offers the possibility to simulate CAN bus activity by sending CAN frames to the bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] The CAN bus monitor can therefore be used to validate expected CAN traffic from a given device or to simulate CAN traffic in order to validate the reaction from a given device connected to the CAN bus.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Bosch holds patents on the technology, though those related to the original protocol have now expired.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of CAN-compatible microprocessors pay license fees to Bosch for use of the CAN trademark and any of the newer patents related to CAN FD, and these are normally passed on to the customer in the price of the chip.
[src:j1939/can-bus-p02] Manufacturers of products with custom ASICs or FPGAs containing CAN-compatible modules need to pay a fee for the CAN Protocol License if they wish to use the CAN trademark or CAN FD capabilities.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] A **commercial vehicle** is any type of motor vehicle used for transporting goods or paying passengers.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Depending on laws and designations, a commercial vehicle can be any broad type of motor vehicle used commercially or for business purposes.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] In the United States, a vehicle is designated "commercial" when it is titled or registered to a company.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] This is a broad definition, as commercial vehicles may be fleet vehicles, company cars, or other vehicles used for business.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Vehicles that are designed to carry more than 15 passengers are considered a commercial vehicle.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Variations may exist from state-to-state on which "commercial vehicles" are prohibited on certain routes and lanes and between homeowner associations, which may employ broader definitions than their municipalities with regard to their own parking restrictions.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] A vehicle can be used for a business, if not exclusively, and remain privately licensed, depending on the amount of time used for business.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Is used in transporting material found by the Secretary of Transportation to be hazardous.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] The federal definition, though followed closely, is meant to accommodate and remain flexible to each state's definitions.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] This means the tanks permanently fixed by the manufacturer to all motor vehicles of the same type as the vehicle in question and whose permanent fitting lets fuel be used directly, both for propulsion and, where appropriate, to power a refrigeration system.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Gas tanks fitted to motor vehicles for the direct use of diesel as a fuel are considered standard fuel tanks.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Commercial trucks are classified according to the gross vehicle weight rating (GVWR).
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Commercial vehicles are divided into eight classes based upon the gross vehicle weight (GVW).
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Commercial vehicles are sometimes sought after for historic preservation as classic cars.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] News about preservation can be found in magazines such as Hemmings Motor News and Heritage Commercials.
[src:j1939/commercial-vehicle] Commercial vehicle accidents and injuries are often more complex than regular car accidents, often involving additional concerns, background checks on operator driving records, and corporate maintenance records.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] An **electronic control unit** (**ECU**), also known as an **electronic control module** (**ECM**), is an embedded system in automotive electronics that controls one or more of the electrical systems or subsystems in a car or other motor vehicle.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] These ECUs together are sometimes referred to collectively as **the car's computer** though technically they are all separate computers, not a single one.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Sometimes an assembly incorporates several individual control modules (a PCM often controls both the engine and the transmission).
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Some modern motor vehicles have up to 150 ECUs.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Embedded software in ECUs continues to increase in line count, complexity, and sophistication.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Managing the increasing complexity and number of ECUs in a vehicle has become a key challenge for original equipment manufacturers (OEMs).
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] The development of an ECU involves both hardware and software required to perform the functions expected from that particular module.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Automotive ECU's are being developed following the V-model.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Recently the trend is to dedicate a significant amount of time and effort to develop safe modules by following standards like ISO 26262.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] It is rare that a module is developed fully from scratch.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] The design is generally iterative and improvements are made to both the hardware and software.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] The development of most ECUs is carried out by Tier 1 suppliers based on specifications provided by the OEM.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] As part of the development cycle, manufacturers perform detailed FMEAs and other failure analyses to catch failure modes that can lead to unsafe conditions or driver annoyance.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Extensive testing and validation activities are carried out as part of the production part approval process to gain the confidence of the hardware and software.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] On-board diagnostics or OBD help provide specific data related to which system or component failed or caused a failure during run time and help perform repairs.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] Some people may wish to modify their ECU so as to be able to add or change functionality.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] However modern ECUs come equipped with protection locks to prevent users from modifying the circuit or exchange chips.
[src:j1939/electronic-control-unit] The protection locks are a form of digital rights management (DRM), the circumventing of which is illegal in certain jurisdictions.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] Society of Automotive Engineers standard **SAE J1939** is the vehicle bus recommended practice used for communication and diagnostics among vehicle components.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] Originating in the car and heavy-duty truck industry in the United States, it is now widely used in other parts of the world.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] SAE J1939 is used in the commercial vehicle area for connection and communication throughout the vehicle, with the physical layer defined in ISO 11898.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] A different physical layer is used between the tractor and trailer, specified in ISO 11992.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] Originally, Controller Area Network (CAN) was not mentioned in J1939, which covered cars and tractor-trailer rigs, and with some dual and triple use 8-bit addresses assigned by the SAE J1939 board.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] CAN was not originally free, but its instruction set did fit in the custom instruction format of J1939.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] Since then, CAN has been included, the chipset for J1939 has been clocked faster, and 16-bit addresses (PGN) have replaced 8-bit addresses.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] J1939, ISO 11783 and NMEA 2000 all share the same high level protocol.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] SAE J1939 can be considered the replacement for the older SAE J1708 and SAE J1587 specifications.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] SAE J1939 defines five layers in the seven-layer OSI network model, and this includes the Controller Area Network (CAN) ISO 11898 specification (using only the 29-bit/"extended" identifier) for the physical and data-link layers.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] The session and presentation layers are not part of the specification.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] The later use of CAN FD is currently discussed.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] All J1939 packets, except for the request packet, contain eight bytes of data and a standard header which contains an index called Parameter Group Number (PGN), which is embedded in the message's 29-bit identifier.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] A PGN identifies a message's function and associated data.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] J1939 attempts to define standard PGNs to encompass a wide range of automotive, agricultural, marine and off-road vehicle purposes.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] A range of PGNs (00FF0016 through 00FFFF16, inclusive) is reserved for proprietary use.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] PGNs define the data which is made up of a variable number of Suspect Parameter Number (SPN) elements defined for unique data.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] For example, there exists a predefined SPN for engine RPM.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] SAE J1939 has been adopted widely by diesel engine manufacturers.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] One driving force behind this is the increasing adoption of the engine Electronic Control Unit (ECU), which provides one method of controlling exhaust gas emissions within United States and European standards.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] The telematics data is used (via Fleet Telematics Systems) by Fleet Management Systems to let fleet operators keep track of vehicle and driver performance, such as fuel consumption, safety events, and repair time.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] Because of the demanding standards, engine development is expensive, and truck-based engines are reused in many fields.
[src:j1939/sae-j1939] Consequently, SAE J1939 can now be found in a range of diesel-powered applications: vehicles (on- and off-road and rail), marine propulsion, power generation and industrial pumping.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE International has over 138,000 global members.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Membership is granted to individuals, rather than companies.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Aside from its standardization efforts, SAE International also devotes resources to projects and programs in STEM education, professional certification, and collegiate design competitions.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] In the early 1900s there were dozens of automobile manufacturers in the United States, and many more worldwide.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Auto manufacturers and parts companies joined trade groups that promoted business.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] A desire to solve common technical design problems and develop engineering standards was emerging.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Engineers in the automobile business expressed a desire to have "free exchange of ideas" to expand their technical knowledge base.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Two magazine publishers, Peter Heldt of *The Horseless Age*, and Horace Swetland of *The Automobile*, were advocates of the concepts for SAE.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Heldt wrote an editorial in June 1902 in which he said, "Now there is a noticeable tendency for automobile manufacturers to follow certain accepted lines of construction, technical questions constantly arise which seek a solution from the cooperation of the technical men connected with the industry.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] These questions could best be dealt with by a technical society.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Horace Swetland wrote on automotive engineering concerns and became an original SAE officer.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] About two years after Heldt's editorial, the Society of Automobile Engineers was founded in New York City.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Four officers and five managing officers volunteered.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Riker served as president, and Henry Ford served as the society's first vice president.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] The initial membership was engineers with annual dues of US$10.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Over the first 10 years, SAE membership grew steadily, and the society added full-time staff and began to publish a technical journal and a comprehensive compilation of technical papers, previously called SAE Transactions, which still exist today in the form of SAE International's Journals.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] At the annual meeting that year, representatives from the American Society of Aeronautic Engineers, the Society of Tractor Engineers, as well as representatives from the power boating industry made a pitch to SAE for oversight of technical standards in their industries.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Aeronautics was a fledgling industry at that time.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Early supporters of the concept of a society to represent aeronautical engineers were Thomas Edison, Glenn Curtiss, Glenn Martin, and Orville Wright.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Out of the meeting in 1916 came a new organization, to represent engineers in all types of mobility-related professions.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE member Elmer Sperry created the term "automotive" from Greek autos (self), and Latin motivus (of motion) origins to represent any form of self-powered vehicle.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] The Society of Automobile Engineers became the Society of Automotive Engineers.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Women joined the SAE in the 1920's, with Marie Luhring becoming an associate member of the organization in 1920.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Bailey became the first woman to become a full member of the SAE in 1926, having joined the staff as a research engineer in 1920.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Charles Kettering presided over SAE during World War I and saw membership pass the 5,000 mark.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] During this time, SAE emphasized the importance of developing member activity through local chapters – called *Sections*.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] After World War II, the Society established links with other standards bodies and automotive engineering societies worldwide, and since then has founded sections in countries including Brazil, India, China, Russia, Romania, and Egypt.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] By 1980, membership surpassed 35,000 and over the next two decades the society, like the industries and individuals it serves, became larger, more global, more diverse, and more electronic.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] By the mid-1980s, membership edged close to 50,000; by the end of the 1990s, membership topped 80,000 with members in more than 80 countries.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] As of 2017, the society serves over 138,000 global members, with more than a quarter from outside of North America.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE International provides a forum for companies, government agencies, research institutions and consultants to devise technical standards and recommended practices for the design, construction, and characteristics of motor vehicle components.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE documents do not carry any legal force, but are in some cases referenced by the U.S.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) and Transport Canada.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE publishes technical documents for the aerospace industry.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Aerospace Recommended Practices are recommendations for engineering practice, and Aerospace Information Reports contain general accepted engineering data and information.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE has proposed an influential categorization for "levels of driving automation" in vehicular automation.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE J3016 defines six levels of automation for cars, ranging from level 0 (No Driving Automation) to level 5 (Full Automation), transitioning gradually from "driver support features" to "automated driving features".
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] This categorization scheme has also been adopted by the NHTSA.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] For historical legacy reasons, the label "SAE" is commonly used on tools and hardware in North America to indicate United States customary units measurements, that is, inch-based not metric (SI).
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Both this usage and casual use of the term "Imperial" are loose and imprecise (but common) references to inch fractional sizes and to the screw thread sizes of the Unified Thread Standard (UTS).
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE has long provided standards for rating automobile horsepower.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Until 1971–1972 SAE gross power was used.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Similar to brake horsepower (bhp), it gave generously unrealistic performance ratings.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Since then, the standard has been the more conservative SAE net power, which takes into account engine accessory, emissions, and exhaust drags, but not transmission losses.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE International has been publishing technical information since 1906.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Industry magazines published monthly include: *Automotive Engineering International*, *Aerospace Engineering and Manufacturing*, *Off Highway Engineering*, *Truck & Bus Engineering*, *SAE Vehicle Engineering*, e-newsletters, Momentum magazine for student members, and various journals.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE also produces the monthly *Update* newsletter for its members and publishes more than 100 books a year in print and electronic formats.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Ranging from compilations on various technical subjects, to textbooks, to historical and enthusiast-oriented books, SAE's titles cater to a variety of readers.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] In April 2007, MIT canceled its subscription to SAE because of required digital rights management (DRM) technology implemented on SAE web-based database of technical papers.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] SAE International removed the DRM restrictions for colleges, universities, and other academic institutions.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] In 1986, SAE International established the *SAE Foundation* to support science and technology education.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] One of the most pressing issues facing industry today is the decline of students enrolling in science and technology programs.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] This decline and its impact threaten the ability to meet future workforce demands.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] The SAE Foundation encourages and supports the development of skills related to mathematics, technology, engineering and science.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] The *SAE Collegiate Design Series* provides an opportunity for college students to go beyond textbook theory and replicates the process of engineering design and manufacturing.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] In the CDS program, a company wants to sell a product for a specific market segment, for example a radio controlled airplane, a single seat off-road vehicle, or a single seat Formula style race car.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Instead of doing all the design, manufacturing and testing in house, the customer chooses to contract out those processes to a supplier, and sends their requirements out for bid.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Student teams act as the suppliers and design, build and test a prototype vehicle that they believe meets the customer's specifications.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] Each team then presents its prototype to the customer at the annual competitions and is judged on several criteria.
[src:j1939/society-of-automotive-engineers] The team with the highest points essentially wins the contract.
[src:j1939/truck] A **truck** (North American and Australian English) or **lorry** (British English) is a motor vehicle designed to transport freight, carry specialized payloads, or perform other utilitarian work.
[src:j1939/truck] Trucks vary greatly in size, power, and configuration, but the vast majority feature body-on-frame construction, with a cabin that is independent of the payload portion of the vehicle.
[src:j1939/truck] Smaller varieties may be mechanically similar to some automobiles.
[src:j1939/truck] Commercial trucks can be very large and powerful and may be configured to be mounted with specialized equipment, such as in the case of refuse trucks, fire trucks, concrete mixers, and suction excavators.
[src:j1939/truck] In American English, a commercial vehicle without a trailer or other articulation is formally a "straight truck" while one designed specifically to pull a trailer is not a truck but a "tractor".
[src:j1939/truck] The majority of trucks currently in use are powered by diesel engines, although small- to medium-size trucks with gasoline engines exist in North America.
[src:j1939/truck] Electrically powered trucks are more popular in China and Europe than elsewhere.
[src:j1939/truck] In the European Union, vehicles with a gross combination mass of up to 3.5 t (3.4 long tons; 3.9 short tons) are defined as light commercial vehicles, and those over as large goods vehicles.
[src:j1939/truck] Steam wagons were not common until the mid-19th century.
[src:j1939/truck] The roads of the time, built for horse and carriages, limited these vehicles to very short hauls, usually from a factory to the nearest railway station.
[src:j1939/truck] The first semi-trailer appeared in 1881, towed by a steam tractor manufactured by De Dion-Bouton.
[src:j1939/truck] Steam-powered wagons were sold in France and the United States until the eve of World War I, and 1935 in the United Kingdom, when a change in road tax rules made them uneconomic against the new diesel lorries.
[src:j1939/truck] In 1895, Karl Benz designed and built the first internal combustion truck.
[src:j1939/truck] Later that year some of Benz's trucks were modified to become busses by *Netphener*.
[src:j1939/truck] A year later, in 1896, another internal combustion engine truck was built by Gottlieb Daimler, the Daimler Motor Lastwagen.
[src:j1939/truck] Other companies, such as Peugeot, Renault and Büssing, also built their own versions.
[src:j1939/truck] The first truck in the United States was built by Autocar in 1899, and was available with 5 or 8 horsepower (4 or 6 kW) engines.
[src:j1939/truck] Another early American truck was built by George Eldridge of Des Moines, Iowa, in 1903.
[src:j1939/truck] It was powered by an engine with two opposed cylinders, and had a chain drive A 1903 Eldridge truck is displayed at the Iowa 80 Trucking Museum, Walcott, Iowa.
[src:j1939/truck] Trucks of the era mostly used two-cylinder engines and had a carrying capacity of 1.5 to 2 t (3,300 to 4,400 lb).
[src:j1939/truck] After World War I, several advances were made: electric starters, and 4, 6, and 8 cylinder engines.
[src:j1939/truck] Although it had been invented in 1897, the diesel engine did not appear in production trucks until Benz introduced it in 1923.
[src:j1939/truck] The diesel engine was not common in trucks in Europe until the 1930s.
[src:j1939/truck] In the United States, Autocar introduced diesel engines for heavy applications in the mid-1930s.
[src:j1939/truck] Demand was high enough that Autocar launched the "DC" model (diesel conventional) in 1939.
[src:j1939/truck] However, it took much longer for diesel engines to be broadly accepted in the US: gasoline engines were still in use on heavy trucks in the 1970s.
[src:j1939/truck] Electrically powered trucks predate internal combustion ones and have been continuously available since the mid-19th-century.
[src:j1939/truck] In the 1920s Autocar Trucks was the first of the major truck manufacturers to offer a range of electric trucks for sale.
[src:j1939/truck] Electric trucks were successful for urban delivery roles and as specialized work vehicles like forklifts and pushback tugs.
[src:j1939/truck] Today, manufacturers are electrifying all trucks ahead of national regulatory requirements, with long-range over-the-road trucks being the most challenging.
[src:j1939/truck] The first known usage of "truck" was in 1611 when it referred to the small strong wheels on ships' cannon carriages, and comes from Greek τροχός (*trokhos*) = "wheel".
[src:j1939/truck] In its extended usage, it came to refer to carts for carrying heavy loads, a meaning known since 1771.
[src:j1939/truck] Its expanded application to "motor-powered load carrier" has been in usage since 1930, shortened from "motor truck", which dates back to 1901.
[src:j1939/truck] "Lorry" has a more uncertain origin, but probably has its roots in the rail transport industry, where the word is known to have been used in 1838 to refer to a type of truck (a goods wagon as in British usage, not a bogie as in the American), specifically a large flat wagon.
[src:j1939/truck] It might derive from the verb *lurry* (to carry or drag along, or to lug) which was in use as early as 1664, but that association is not definitive.
[src:j1939/truck] The expanded meaning of *lorry*, "self-propelled vehicle for carrying goods", has been in usage since 1911.
[src:j1939/truck] In the United States, Canada, and the Philippines, "truck" is usually reserved for commercial vehicles larger than regular passenger cars, but includes large SUVs, pickups, and other vehicles with an open load bed.
[src:j1939/truck] In Australia, New Zealand and South Africa, the word "truck" is mostly reserved for larger vehicles.
[src:j1939/truck] In Australia and New Zealand, a pickup truck is frequently called a *ute* (short for "utility" vehicle), while in South Africa it is called a *bakkie* (Afrikaans: "small open container").
[src:j1939/truck] In the United Kingdom, India, Malaysia, Singapore, Ireland, and Hong Kong *lorry* is used instead of *truck*, but only for the medium and heavy types, while *truck* is used almost exclusively to refer to pickups.
[src:j1939/truck] Often produced as variations of golf cars, with internal combustion or battery electric drive, these are used typically for off-highway use on estates, golf courses, and parks.
[src:j1939/truck] While not suitable for highway use some variations may be licensed as slow speed vehicles for operation on streets, generally as a body variation of a neighborhood electric vehicle.
[src:j1939/truck] A few manufactures produce specialized chassis for this type of vehicle, while Zap Motors markets a version of their Xebra electric tricycle (licensable in the U.S. as a motorcycle).
[src:j1939/truck] Popular in Europe and Asia, many mini-trucks are factory redesigns of light automobiles, usually with monocoque bodies.
[src:j1939/truck] Specialized designs with substantial frames such as the Italian Piaggio shown here are based upon Japanese designs (in this case by Daihatsu) and are popular for use in "old town" sections of European cities that often have very narrow alleyways.
[src:j1939/truck] Regardless of name, these small trucks serve a wide range of uses.
[src:j1939/truck] In Japan, they are regulated under the Kei car laws, which allow vehicle owners a break in taxes for buying a smaller and less-powerful vehicle (currently, the engine is limited to 660 cc displacement).
[src:j1939/truck] These vehicles are used as on-road utility vehicles in Japan.
[src:j1939/truck] These Japanese-made mini-trucks that were manufactured for on-road use are competing with off-road ATVs in the United States, and import regulations require that these mini-trucks have a 25 mph (40 km/h) speed governor as they are classified as low-speed vehicles.
[src:j1939/truck] These vehicles have found uses in construction, large campuses (government, university, and industrial), agriculture, cattle ranches, amusement parks, and replacements for golf carts.
[src:j1939/truck] Major mini-truck manufacturers and their brands include: Daihatsu Hijet, Honda Acty, Tata Ace, Mazda Scrum, Mitsubishi Minicab, Subaru Sambar, and Suzuki Carry.
[src:j1939/truck] Light trucks are car-sized (in the US, no more than 13,900 lb (6.3 t)) and are used by individuals and businesses alike.
[src:j1939/truck] In the EU they may not weigh more than 3.5 t (7,700 lb) and are allowed to be driven with a driving licence for cars.
[src:j1939/truck] Pickup trucks, called *utes* in Australia and New Zealand, are common in North America and some regions of Latin America, Asia, and Africa, but not so in Europe, where this size of commercial vehicle is most often made as vans.
[src:j1939/truck] Medium trucks are larger than light but smaller than heavy trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] In the US, they are defined as weighing between 13,000 and 33,000 lb (5.9 and 15.0 t).
[src:j1939/truck] For the UK and the EU the weight is between 3.5 and 7.5 t (7,700 and 16,500 lb).
[src:j1939/truck] Local delivery and public service (dump trucks, garbage trucks and fire-fighting trucks) are normally around this size.
[src:j1939/truck] Heavy trucks are the largest on-road trucks, Class 8.
[src:j1939/truck] These include vocational applications such as heavy dump trucks, concrete pump trucks, and refuse hauling, as well as ubiquitous long-haul 4x2 and 6×4 tractor units.
[src:j1939/truck] Road damage and wear increase very rapidly with the axle weight.
[src:j1939/truck] The number of steering axles and the suspension type also influence the amount of the road wear.
[src:j1939/truck] In many countries with good roads a six-axle truck may have a maximum weight of 44 t (97,000 lb) or more.
[src:j1939/truck] Australia has complex regulations over weight and length, including axle spacing, type of axle/axle group, rear overhang, kingpin to rear of trailer, drawbar length, ground clearance, as well as height and width laws.
[src:j1939/truck] These limits are some of the highest in the world, a B-double can weigh 62.5 t (61.5 long tons; 68.9 short tons) and be 25 m (82 ft) long, and road trains used in the outback can weigh 172 t (169.3 long tons; 189.6 short tons) and be 53.5 m (176 ft) long.
[src:j1939/truck] The European Union also has complex regulations.
[src:j1939/truck] The number and spacing of axles, steering, single or dual tires, and suspension type all affect maximum weights.
[src:j1939/truck] Length of a truck, of a trailer, from axle to hitch point, kingpin to rear of trailer, and turning radius are all regulated.
[src:j1939/truck] In additions, there are special rules for carrying containers, and countries can set their own rules for local traffic.
[src:j1939/truck] The United States Federal Bridge Law deals with the relation between the gross weight of the truck, the number of axles, the weight on and the spacing between the axles that the truck can have on the Interstate highway system.
[src:j1939/truck] Each State determines the maximum permissible vehicle, combination, and axle weight on state and local roads.
[src:j1939/truck] Uniquely, the State of Michigan has a gross vehicle weight limit of 164,000 lb (74 t), which is twice the U.S. federal limit.
[src:j1939/truck] A measure to change the law was defeated in the Michigan Senate in 2019.
[src:j1939/truck] Almost all trucks share a common construction: they are made of a chassis, a cab, an area for placing cargo or equipment, axles, suspension and roadwheels, an engine and a drivetrain.
[src:j1939/truck] Pneumatic, hydraulic, water, and electrical systems may also be present.
[src:j1939/truck] Many also tow one or more trailers or semi-trailers.
[src:j1939/truck] The "cab", or "cabin" is an enclosed space where the driver is seated.
[src:j1939/truck] A "sleeper" is a compartment attached to or integral with the cab where the driver can rest while not driving, sometimes seen in semi-trailer trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] A further step from this is the side loading forklift that can be described as a specially fabricated vehicle with the same properties as a truck of this type, in addition to the ability to pick up its own load.
[src:j1939/truck] Most small trucks such as sport utility vehicles (SUVs), vans or pickups, and even light medium-duty trucks in North America, China, and Russia use gasoline engines (petrol engines), but many diesel engined models are now being produced.
[src:j1939/truck] Most of the heavier trucks use four-stroke diesel engines with a turbocharger and intercooler.
[src:j1939/truck] Huge off-highway trucks use locomotive-type engines such as a V12 Detroit Diesel two stroke engine.
[src:j1939/truck] A large proportion of refuse trucks in the United States employ CNG (compressed natural gas) engines for their low fuel cost and reduced carbon emissions.
[src:j1939/truck] A significant proportion of North American manufactured trucks use an engine built by the last remaining major independent engine manufacturer (Cummins) but most global OEMs such as Volvo Trucks and Daimler AG promote their own "captive" engines.
[src:j1939/truck] In the European Union, all new truck engines must comply with Euro VI emission regulations, and Euro 7 from the late 2020s has stricter exhaust limits and also limits air pollution from brakes and tires.
[src:j1939/truck] As of 2019 several alternative technologies are competing to displace the use of diesel engines in heavy trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] CNG engines are widely used in the US refuse industry and in concrete mixers, among other short-range vocations, but range limitations have prevented their broader uptake in freight hauling applications.
[src:j1939/truck] Heavy electric trucks and hydrogen-powered trucks are new to the market in 2021, but major freight haulers are interested.
[src:j1939/truck] Although cars will be first the phase-out of fossil fuel vehicles includes trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] According to The Economist magazine "Electric lorries will probably run on hydrogen, not batteries, which are too expensive." Other researchers say that once faster chargers are available batteries will become competitive against diesel for all, except perhaps the heaviest, trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] Small trucks use the same type of transmissions as almost all cars, having either an automatic transmission or a manual transmission with synchromesh (synchronizers).
[src:j1939/truck] Bigger trucks often use manual transmissions without synchronizers, saving bulk and weight, although synchromesh transmissions are used in larger trucks as well.
[src:j1939/truck] Finally, the clutch pedal is released and the accelerator pedal pushed down to obtain the required engine speed.
[src:j1939/truck] Although this is a relatively fast movement, perhaps a second or so while the transmission is in neutral, it allows the engine speed to drop and synchronize engine and transmission revolutions relative to the road speed.
[src:j1939/truck] Downshifting is performed in a similar fashion, except the engine speed is now required to increase (while the transmission is in neutral) just the right amount in order to achieve the synchronization for a smooth, non-collision gear change.
[src:j1939/truck] "Skip changing" is also widely used; in principle, the operation is the same as double-clutching, but it requires neutral be held slightly longer than a single-gear change.
[src:j1939/truck] Common North American setups include 9, 10, 13, 15, and 18 speeds.
[src:j1939/truck] Automatic and automated manual transmissions for heavy trucks are becoming more and more common, due to advances both in transmission and engine power.
[src:j1939/truck] In Europe, 8, 10, 12, and 16 gears are common on larger trucks with a manual transmission, while conventional automatic or automated manual transmissions would have anything from 5 to 12 gears.
[src:j1939/truck] Almost all heavy truck transmissions are of the "range and split" (double H shift pattern) type, where range change and so‑called half gears or splits are air operated and always preselected before the main gear selection.
[src:j1939/truck] A truck frame consists of two parallel boxed (tubular) or C‑shaped rails, or beams, held together by crossmembers.
[src:j1939/truck] These frames are referred to as ladder frames due to their resemblance to a ladder if tipped on end.
[src:j1939/truck] The rails consist of a tall vertical section (two if boxed) and two shorter horizontal flanges.
[src:j1939/truck] The height of the vertical section provides opposition to vertical flex when weight is applied to the top of the frame (beam resistance).
[src:j1939/truck] Though typically flat the whole length on heavy-duty trucks, the rails may sometimes be tapered or arched for clearance around the engine or over the axles.
[src:j1939/truck] The holes in rails are used either for mounting vehicle components and running wires and hoses or measuring and adjusting the orientation of the rails at the factory or repair shop.
[src:j1939/truck] The frame is usually made of steel, but can be made (whole or in part) of aluminum for a lighter weight.
[src:j1939/truck] A tow bar may be found attached at one or both ends, but heavy tractors almost always make use of a fifth wheel hitch.
[src:j1939/truck] In many countries, driving a truck requires a special driving license.
[src:j1939/truck] The requirements and limitations vary with each different jurisdiction.
[src:j1939/truck] In Australia, a truck driver's license is required for any motor vehicle with a gross vehicle mass (GVM) exceeding 4.5 t (4.4 long tons; 5.0 short tons).
[src:j1939/truck] There is also a heavy vehicle transmission condition for a license class *HC*, *HR*, or *MC* test passed in a vehicle fitted with an automatic or synchromesh transmission; a driver's license will be restricted to vehicles of that class fitted with a synchromesh or automatic transmission.
[src:j1939/truck] To have the condition removed, a person needs to pass a practical driving test in a vehicle with non-synchromesh transmission (constant mesh or crash box).
[src:j1939/truck] Driving licensing has been harmonized throughout the European Union and the EEA (and practically all European non-member states), so that common rules apply within Europe (see European driving licence).
[src:j1939/truck] As an overview, to drive a vehicle weighing more than 7.5 t (7.4 long tons; 8.3 short tons) for commercial purposes requires a specialist license (the type varies depending on the use of the vehicle and number of seats).
[src:j1939/truck] For licenses first acquired after 1997, that weight was reduced to 3.5 t (3.4 long tons; 3.9 short tons), not including trailers.
[src:j1939/truck] Since 2013, the C1 license category allows driving vehicles over 3.5 and up to 7.5 tonnes.
[src:j1939/truck] The C license category allows driving vehicles over 3.5 tonnes with a trailer up to 750 kg, and the CE category allows driving category C vehicles with a trailer over 750 kg.
[src:j1939/truck] To drive any vehicle with a GVM exceeding 3.5 t (3.4 long tons; 3.9 short tons), a code C1 drivers license is required.
[src:j1939/truck] Furthermore, if the vehicle exceeds 16 t (15.7 long tons; 17.6 short tons) a code C license becomes necessary.
[src:j1939/truck] To drive any vehicle in South Africa towing a trailer with a GVM more than 7.5 t (7.4 long tons; 8.3 short tons), further restrictions apply and the driver must possess a license suitable for the GVM of the total combination as well as an articulated endorsement.
[src:j1939/truck] This is indicated with the letter "E" prefixing the license code.
[src:j1939/truck] In addition, any vehicle designed to carry goods or passengers may only be driven by a driver possessing a Public Driver's Permit, (or PrDP) of the applicable type.
[src:j1939/truck] This is an additional license that is added to the DL card of the operator and subject to annual renewal unlike the five-year renewal period of a normal license.
[src:j1939/truck] The requirements for obtaining the different classes are below.
[src:j1939/truck] In the United States, a commercial driver's license is required to drive any type of commercial vehicle weighing 26,001 lb (11,794 kg) or more.
[src:j1939/truck] Instruments to track each driver's hours must sometimes be fitted.
[src:j1939/truck] In 2006, the US trucking industry employed 1.8 million drivers of heavy trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] There is a shortage of willing trained long-distance truck drivers.
[src:j1939/truck] Part of the reason for this is the economic fallout from deregulation of the trucking industry.
[src:j1939/truck] Belzer, associate professor, in the economics department at Wayne State University and co-author of *Sweatshops on Wheels: Winners and Losers in Trucking Deregulation*, argues that low pay, bad working conditions and unsafe conditions have been a direct result of deregulation.
[src:j1939/truck] The book cites poor working conditions and an unfair pay system as responsible for high annual employee turnover in the industry.
[src:j1939/truck] Like cars, trucks contribute to air, noise, and water pollution.
[src:j1939/truck] Unlike cars, as of 2022, most trucks run on diesel, and diesel exhaust is especially dangerous for health.
[src:j1939/truck] Some countries outside the EU have different vehicle emission standards for trucks and cars.
[src:j1939/truck] NOx and particulates emitted by trucks are very dangerous to health, causing thousands of early deaths annually in the US alone.
[src:j1939/truck] As older trucks are usually the worst, many cities have banned 20th century trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] Air pollution also threatens professional truck drivers.
[src:j1939/truck] Over a quarter of global transport CO2 emissions are from road freight, in 2021 over 1700 million tonnes from medium and heavy trucks, so many countries are further restricting truck CO2 emissions to help limit climate change.
[src:j1939/truck] Many environmental organizations favor laws and incentives to encourage the switch from road to rail, especially in Europe.
[src:j1939/truck] Several countries have pledged that 30% of sales of trucks and buses will be zero emission by 2030.
[src:j1939/truck] With respect to noise pollution, trucks emit considerably higher sound levels at all speeds compared to typical cars; this contrast is particularly strong with heavy-duty trucks.
[src:j1939/truck] There are several aspects of truck operations that contribute to the overall sound that is emitted.
[src:j1939/truck] Continuous sounds are those from tires rolling on the roadway and the constant hum of their diesel engines at highway speeds.
[src:j1939/truck] Less frequent noises, but perhaps more noticeable, are things like the repeated sharp-pitched whistle of a turbocharger on acceleration, or the abrupt blare of an exhaust brake retarder when traversing a downgrade.
[src:j1939/truck] There has been noise regulation put in place to help control where and when the use of engine braking retarders are allowed.
[src:j1939/truck] A truck cab is a hazard control that protects the truck operator from hazardous airborne pollutants.
[src:j1939/truck] As an enclosure, it is an example of an engineering control.
[src:j1939/truck] Enclosed operator cabs have been used on agriculture, mining, and construction vehicles for several decades.
[src:j1939/truck] Most modern-day enclosed cabs have heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems for primarily maintaining a comfortable temperature and providing breathable air for their occupants.
[src:j1939/truck] Various levels of filtration can be incorporated into the HVAC system to remove airborne pollutants such as dusts, diesel particulate matter (DPM), and other aerosols.
[src:j1939/truck] Two key elements of an effective environmental enclosure are a good filtration system and an enclosure with good integrity (sealed isolation from the outside environment).
[src:j1939/truck] It is recommended that a filtration system filter out at least 95% or greater of airborne respirable aerosols from the intake airflow, with an additional recirculation filtering component for the inside air.
[src:j1939/truck] Good enclosure integrity is also needed to achieve positive pressure to prevent wind-driven aerosol penetration into the enclosure*,* as well as to minimize air leakage around the filtration system.
[src:j1939/truck] Test methods and mathematical modeling of environmental enclosures are also beneficial for quantifying and optimizing filtration system designs, as well as maintaining optimum protection factor performance for enclosure occupants.
[src:j1939/truck] Commercial trucks in the US pay higher road use taxes on a state level than other road vehicles and are subject to extensive regulation.
[src:j1939/truck] A few reasons commercial trucks pay higher road use taxes: they are bigger and heavier than most other vehicles, and cause more wear and tear per hour on roadways; and trucks and their drivers are on the road for more hours per day.
[src:j1939/truck] Rules on use taxes differ among jurisdictions.
[src:j1939/truck] The life of a pavement is measured by the number of passes of a vehicle axle.
[src:j1939/truck] It may be evaluated using the Load Equivalency Factor, which states that the damage by the pass of a vehicle axle is proportional to the 4th power of the weight, so a ten-ton axle consumes 10,000 times the life of the pavement as a one-ton axle.
[src:j1939/truck] For that reason, loaded trucks cost the same as thousands of cars in pavement costs, and are subject to higher taxes and highway tolls.
[src:j1939/truck] In 2002 and 2004, there were over 5,000 fatalities related to trucking accidents in the United States.
[src:j1939/truck] The trucking industry has since made significant efforts in increasing safety regulations.
[src:j1939/truck] In 2008, the industry had successfully lowered the fatality rate to just over 4,000 deaths, but trucking accidents are still an issue that causes thousands of deaths and injuries each year.
[src:j1939/truck] Approximately 6,000 trucking accident fatalities occur annually in the United States.
[src:j1939/truck] Fatalities are not the only issue caused by trucking accidents.
[src:j1939/truck] Following increased pressure from *The Times* "Cities Fit For Cycling" campaign and from other media in Spring 2012, warning signs are now displayed on the backs of many heavy goods vehicles (HGV).
[src:j1939/truck] These signs are directed against a common type of accident that occurs when the large vehicle turns left at a junction: a cyclist trying to pass on the nearside can be crushed against the HGV's wheels, especially if the driver cannot see the cyclist.
[src:j1939/truck] The signs, such as the winning design of the InTANDEM road safety competition launched in March 2012, advocate extra care when passing a large vehicle on the nearside.
[src:j1939/truck] In-vehicle speed limitation is required applying a 90 km/h limit to commercial vehicles over 3.5 tonnes.
[src:j1939/truck] Front, side, and rear underrun protection is required on commercial vehicles over 3.5 tonnes.
[src:j1939/truck] Trucks must be fitted with blind-spot mirrors that give drivers a wider field of vision than conventional mirrors.
